{"id":27,"date":"2020-01-15T18:15:00","date_gmt":"2020-01-15T18:15:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/blueocea.local\/blog-post-title-one-59lws\/"},"modified":"2021-06-14T22:40:31","modified_gmt":"2021-06-15T05:40:31","slug":"blog-post-title-one-59lws","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/blueocea.local\/blog-post-title-one-59lws\/","title":{"rendered":"Keep your tax &amp; financial documents for at least 11 years"},"content":{"rendered":"<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">Personal taxes can be complicated. #Business #Taxes can be even more difficult. If you own a small business, tax time can be challenging.<strong><em> The livelihood of any company is at least partially dependent on its ability to minimize its tax liability, while meeting the requirements of the IRS. <\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;If you\u2019re ever audited, you\u2019ll need those records. <strong><em>Any claims made at tax time require supporting documentation.<\/em><\/strong> Keeping good records is an excellent idea for any small business because it encourages organization. It is very difficult to reconstruct records at a later date.<\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">So why 11 years, when you always hear 7 years? <\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">Well for starters when you file taxes you are filing for at least a year behind. For example you file by March 15th, 2020 (for #Partnerships, #S-Corps, #C-Corps, #Trusts &amp; #Estate returns) for 2019\u2019s tax year, if you are on a calendar year. With an extension you can push that out to September 15th.  But if you are on a fiscal year, you may actually push that out even further. <\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">The IRS can randomly check the last 3 years for accuracy. If they find anything that feels fishy and then audit you (Whether you know it or not) and then find anything, anything at all, they can go back and audit another 3 years, from the date of the filing, not of the close of the year. They will usually stop there if they do not find anything but but they have the option of going back to the last ten from the last tax return you have filed.<\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">Let me repeat: If you have not filed. the IRS can audit back to 10 years previous to the last time you filed.<\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">So for example, I served a gentleman that has not filed his taxes in 15 years. The IRS could audit his tax returns for the last 25 years because of this statute of limitations. But if he had filed all the way along, They could only audit back the last ten due to the limit based on the Statute of limitations.<\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">Or another way, if you filed in 2020 for tax year 2019, they can go all the way back to your 2009 tax filing. <\/p>\n<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">Keep your records and act legally and ethically. Don\u2019t give them a reason to audit you. <\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p class=\"\" style=\"white-space:pre-wrap;\">When they told you to hold on to your documents for 7 years they kind of undershot it. <\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":28,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[2],"tags":[],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v17.8 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>Keep your tax &amp; financial documents for at least 11 years - Blue Ocean Consulting<\/title>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/blueocea.local\/blog-post-title-one-59lws\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_US\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:ti